p.said:
Isabella talked of his attentions;
                        she had never been sensible of any; but Isabella had said many things which
                        she hoped had been spoken in haste, and would never be said again;

though as careless on such subjects
                        as most people, he did look upon a tolerably large eating-room as one of the
                        necessaries of life;

In short, she could not
                        sleep till she had examined it. So, placing the candle with great caution on
                        a chair, she seized the key with a very tremulous hand and tried to turn it;
                        but it resisted her utmost strength. Alarmed, but not discouraged, she tried
                        it another way; a bolt flew, and she believed herself successful;

her unwillingness that he should
